    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-02-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-02-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="469"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d469">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.48/1049</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chief of the Division of Far Eastern
                        Affairs</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Hornbeck</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-02-25">February 25,
                            1936</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#nowrap #top">Conversation:</cell>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Sao-Ke Alfred Sze, Chinese Ambassador;</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Hornbeck;</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Mackay.</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>The Ambassador called and said that he had a telegram from H. H. Kung in which
                    Kung instructed him to inquire whether it would be agreeable to the American
                    Government, pending negotiation, as the Chinese Government was sending someone
                    to this country to negotiate on the subject, to let stand in abeyance the
                    payment of $420,000 which will be due from the Chinese Government on March 1 on
                    the RFC credit.</p>
                <p>Mr. Hornbeck called Mr. Mackay in. Mr. Hornbeck inquired on what ground the
                    Chinese Government wished that the payment be held in abeyance. The Ambassador
                    replied that Kung had not informed him but that he supposed that they were “hard
                    up”. Mr. Hornbeck said that we would have to submit the question to the RFC.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>S[<hi rend="smallcaps">tanley</hi>] K. H[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >ornbeck</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
